Assignment 2: Monte Carlo, TD Methods and Function Approximation¶

Tic Tac Toe via Monte Carlo¶

About the environment and episodes:¶

  • In any episode of Tic Tac Toe we will only observe a state once. (So, in case of on-policy MC we will be following first visit MC)
  • The reward for winning if +1 award player 'O' and -1 for player 'X'.
  • Reward for any non winning move is 0.
  • It is prefered to be the first player because he has greater chance of forcing a win. The second player to can only force a tie at best if both players optimally.
  • For the episodes generated we alternatively set 'X' and 'O' as first players so more states can be covered in both on-policy and off-policy methods.

On policy Monte Carlo¶

  • As it is a 2 player game we have use a variation of MC similar to the minimax approach.
  • As each action is deterministic and there is no reward for taking an action: Q(s,a) = V(s'), where s is the current state, a an action and s' is the state reached on taking an action a in state s.
  • As Q(s,a) = V(s'), just maintaining the state values will help us make our policy.
  • As this is an on-policy method, to have exploration along with exploitation we use an $\epsilon$ greedy policy. (with $\epsilon$ = 0.1)
  • Learning state values:
    • We choose 'O' as the maximising agent as it gets positive reward for winning and by maximising the reward it will maximise the chance of winning.
    • Similarly, 'X' chosen to be the minimising agent.
    • A seperate function is made for learning the state values, called "learn_on_policy".
    • We make 2 agent instances, one 'O' and the other 'X' to play the episodes.
    • The function generates the episodes. Each episode is played out by taking steps as given by the agent policies.
    • We reverse the order of states observed and update the on policy monte carlo class according to current state and the total discounted value observed after that state. (The state values is a class variable as the state values don't change for different agents.)
  • Policy:
    • A random number between 0 to 1 is generated if it is less than $\epsilon$. We choose an action randomly
    • Otherwise we choose the action with maximum or minimum value according to the agent agent.

Off policy Monte Carlo¶

  • Similar to on policy the game needs to be modified for 2 players.
  • I have chosen to use off-policy Monte Carlo control method, based on generalized policy iteration and weighted imporatnce sampling.
  • The previous assumption, Q(s,a) = V(s'), still holds.
  • Our behaviour policy is: a random policy i.e. each available action has equal probability of being chosen.
  • Learning state values:
    • We choose 'O' as the maximising agent as it gets positive reward for winning and by maximising the reward it will maximise the chance of winning.
    • Similarly, 'X' chosen to be the minimising agent.
    • A seperate function is made for learning the state values, called "learn_off_policy".
    • We make 2 agent instances, one 'O' and the other 'X' to play the episodes.
    • The function generates the episodes. Each episode is played out by taking steps as given by the agent policies.
    • We reverse the order of states observed and update the on policy monte carlo class according to current state and the weighted value of that state. (The state values is a class variable as the state values don't change for different agents.)
  • Policy:
    • We choose the action with maximum or minimum value according to the agent agent.

Tranining curve¶

  • The TD agent we are comparing with has gone through 17000 episodes of learning.
  • The values learnt after learn_on_policy and learn_off_policy are updated on running those functions again i.e. if you first ran the learn function for 5 episodes and then run it again for 5 episodes, the state values would be equivalent to running it for 10 episodes.
  • The agents chose the first available action or the first action with highest reward always to break ties.
  • The confidence intervals for MC agent and the TD agent are mirror images which is expected as TicTacToe is a zero sum game.
  • On-Policy:
    • Does better than the base agent without any training and gain even more reward after training.
    • Converges/learns faster and has a similar bound as the TD agent in under 5000 episodes.
    • The performance improves with the increase in number of states explored.
  • Off-Policy
    • Does better than the base agent for most of the iterations. The performance is worse
    • Slower learning. It takes about 7,500 episodes for it to perform consistently better than base agent.
    • The performance off-policy agent observeabout 50,000 episodes before we can see a consistent improvement or similar play as TD Agent.
    • For the base agent the performance of both algorithms improve with the number of states explored once significat number of states have been explored.

Frozen Lake through TD methods¶

General Overview¶

  • We use the FrozenLake8x8-v0 environment which has is_slippery set to true by default.
  • As actions are non deterministic, storing only state values isn't sufficient we need to store value of state-action pairs
  • Reward for reaching goal state is 1 and 0 for all other actions including falling in a hole. This causes a unique problem, as grid is huge and slippery if we set initial values of state-ation pairs as 0 (and the environment agent takes the first maximum option always) our state values are never updated beyond 0 (as agent keeps on falling into the whole.)
  • We take inital reward values as 1 to tackle this so we will move from maximum possible value of any state-action pair to it's real value. In this case we would have to change the update values for the agent to incorprate that when an action leads to goal state to not incorporate the next states value in the update formula.

SARSA¶

  • Task is to learn and $\epsilon$ greedy policy. (On observing a few $\epsilon$ values it was observed lower the epsilon faster learning by our agent. We have finally taken $\epsilon$ = 0.01, to maintain exploration and exploitation balance.)
  • As no function like available_actions is present we assume all 4 actions to be possible in any state and the value table is made accordingly.
  • Learning state values:
    • A seperate function is made for learning the state-action pair values, called "learn_sarsa".
    • The function generates the episodes. Each episode is played out by taking steps as given by the agent policies.
    • Everytime a state is encountered and an action is taken:
      • If it leads to a goal or hole we update the state action pair as $Q(s,a) += \alpha\ast(reward - Q(s,a))$, where s is the current state, a is the action taken in the state and Q is the values table. We do this as no action would be taken in the next state and it's value remains equal to 1 whereas it should have been 0 i.e. shouldn't have a contribution.
      • Otherwise, $Q(s,a) += \alpha\ast(reward + \delta\ast Q(s',a') - Q(s,a))$, where s' is the next state and a' is the action taken in next state acccording to the $\epsilon$ greedy policy.
  • Policy:
    • We give $\epsilon$/4 probability to all actions initially and then the action with highest value is given 1 - $\epsilon$ more value.
    • Numpy's random choice function is used to choose an action with appropriate probabilities.

Q-Learning¶

  • Task is to learn a greedy policy.
  • We use an $\epsilon$ greedy policy as our behaviour policy.(with $\epsilon$ = 0.01, we decide to do this as when we chose a completely random policy in Off-policy MC the results observed were mixed, so maybe using an $\epsilon$ greedy policy might give better results)
  • As no function like available_actions is present we assume all 4 actions to be possible in any state and the value table is made accordingly.
  • Learning state values:
    • A seperate function is made for learning the state-action pair values, called "learn_ql".
    • The function generates the episodes. Each episode is played out by taking steps as given by the agent policies.
    • Everytime a state is encountered and an action is taken:
      • If it leads to a goal or hole we update the state action pair as $Q(s,a) += \alpha\ast(reward - Q(s,a))$, where s is the current state, a is the action taken in the state and Q is the values table. We do this as no action would be taken in the next state and it's value remains equal to 1 whereas it should have been 0 i.e. shouldn't have a contribution.
      • Otherwise, $Q(s,a) += \alpha\ast(reward + \delta\ast \max\{Q(s',a')\} - Q(s,a))$, where s' is the next state and a' is the action taken in next state acccording to the $\epsilon$ greedy policy.
    • A seprate function was also prepared for the epsilon greedy policy.
  • Policy:
    • We take the action with the maximum value.

Expected SARSA¶

  • We implement on-policy Expected SARSA. (Due, to easily available pseudo code and ease of implementation.)
  • Hence can use the same SARSA class for agent as before. Only change is making a new function which updates according to the expected value.
  • Task is to learn and $\epsilon$ greedy policy. ($\epsilon$ = 0.01)
  • As no function like available_actions is present we assume all 4 actions to be possible in any state and the value table is made accordingly.
  • Learning state values:
    • A seperate function is made for learning the state-action pair values, called "learn_esarsa".
    • The function generates the episodes. Each episode is played out by taking steps as given by the agent policies.
    • Everytime a state is encountered and an action is taken:
      • If it leads to a goal or hole we update the state action pair as $Q(s,a) += \alpha\ast(reward - Q(s,a))$, where s is the current state, a is the action taken in the state and Q is the values table. We do this as no action would be taken in the next state and it's value remains equal to 1 whereas it should have been 0 i.e. shouldn't have a contribution.
      • Otherwise, $Q(s,a) += \alpha\ast(reward + \delta\ast \sum_a [\pi(a'|s')Q(s',a')] - Q(s,a))$, where s' is the next state and a' is the action taken in next state acccording to the $\epsilon$ greedy policy.
    • A seprate function was also prepared to calculate the ecpected value give value of actions taken in that state.
  • Policy:
    • We give $\epsilon$/4 probability to all actions initially and then the action with highest value is given 1 - $\epsilon$ more value.
    • Numpy's random choice function is used to choose an action with appropriate probabilities.

Curves¶

  • In each run the algorithms go through 10 training iterations.
  • Both Sarsa algorithms seem to have a similar performance.
  • Q-Learning has better performance then both the SARSA alhorithms.
  • FrozenLake-v0 (4x4) stable average rewards:
    • Sarsa: 3
    • Q-Learning: 6
    • Expected Sarsa: 3.1/3.2
  • FrozenLake8x8-v0 stable average reward:
    • Sarsa: 3.5
    • Q-Learning: 6
    • Expected Sarsa: 3

Function Approximation: DQN¶

Introduction¶

We design a model is for playing Breakout. It is an arcade game developed and published by Atari, Inc., and released on May 13, 1976. It was conceptualized by Nolan Bushnell and Steve Bristow, influenced by the seminal 1972 Atari arcade game Pong, and built by Steve Wozniak, aided by Steve Jobs.

We try to follow the approach in the paper "Playing Atari with Deep Reinforcement Learning" whose authors are from DeepMind Technologies. The model is a convolutional neural network, trained with Q-learning, whose input is raw pixels and whose output is a value function estimating futurerewards.

Along with basic Q-learning methods we use: Experience Replay and Target Network.

Experience Replay¶

Store experience (S, A, R, S_next) in a replay buffer and sample minibatches from it to train the network. This decorrelates the data and leads to better data efficiency. In the beginning, the replay buffer is filled with random experience.

Target Network¶

Use a separate network to estimate the TD target. This target network has the same architecture as the function approximator but with frozen parameters. Every T steps (a hyperparameter) the parameters from the Q network are copied to the target network. This leads to more stable training because it keeps the target function fixed (for a while).

Neural Network for function approximation¶

By using a Convolutional Neural Network as the function approximator on raw pixels of Atari games where the score is the reward we can learn to play many of those games at human-like performance.

Implementation¶

We use tensorflow to implement the model. The model implementation is taken from Denny Britz's implementation of Deep Q Learning for the breakout game.

For the implementation of the the DQN code we use Tensorflow version 1.14.0 as version 2.0 isn't fully supported yet and runs into the error "Variable tf.Variable has 'None' for gradient in TensorFlow Probability" for a lot of loss simple functions.

Pre-Processing the Image¶

  • The edges of the image are cut-off and it is downsampled to an 80x80 image.
  • Then the image is converted into a grayscale image.

The DQN Agent¶

  • The Agent requires 3 parameters: model, target model and number of actions. We can also change the discount factor for the agent.
  • The agent provides us with 4 basic functionalities: copying model to the target model, making a greedy move, making an $\epsilon$ greedy move and updating the model from the state-action pairs generated.
  • Update:
    • We generate the values for next state. The target values is created as: $$ target = reward + discount\_rate * max\_action\_val,\ done = False$$ $$ target = reward,\ done = True$$
    • The the state, action and target values are passed to the model for updation.

Learning¶

A large part of getting data for plotting has also been shifted to learning.

  • We first start by getting a random set of states to get the Q value approximation for. (This is done only once.)
  • A tensorflow session is created to run each iteration/epoch for for plotting data.
  • Directories paths are made to store and get data from.
  • We create an array of reducing epsilons so that we have higher exploration in the initial episodes and higher exploitation in the latter.
  • The replay memory is filled.
  • We run certain number of episodes and for each step in the episode:
    • The state is first processed and a stack with the previous 3 frames is made. (For the starting the state we use the same 4 frames.)
    • The state, action, reward, done tuple is added to the memory.
    • A minibatch is sampled from the replay memory and the agent is updated.
  • We run 3 games to calculate the rewards earned.
  • We then get the average values for the set of random states.

The CNN model¶

  • We build the model using tensorflow graphs.
  • It starts withnormalizing the input states between 0 and 1.
  • The model has 3 convolution layers with relu activation function.
  • This is follow by 2 fully connected layers. (One with 512 outputs and other with 4.)
  • The last connected layer gives us the prediction. (Graph for predicting values for states stops here.)
  • We get the predicted q-value for the state, action pairs.
  • MSE is used to calculate the loss.
  • We use the RMSOptimizer with a learning rate = 0.00025, decay rate = 0.99, momentum = 0.0 and epsilon = 1e-6
  • Then the model is updated and a summary is created. (Graph for updating values ends here.)

Convolution Layer¶

The term convolution refers to the mathematical combination of two functions to produce a third function. It merges two sets of information. In the case of a CNN, the convolution is performed on the input data with the use of a filter or kernel to then produce a feature map.

Activation Function¶

Activation function decides, whether a neuron should be activated or not by calculating weighted sum and further adding bias with it. The purpose of the activation function is to introduce non-linearity into the output of a neuron making it capable to learn and perform more complex tasks.

Fully Connected Layer¶

A fully connected layer is generally defined as a matrix multiply: y = f(w x + b) where f is given by activation_fn. If activation_fn is None, the result of y = w x + b is returned.

The layer creates w and optionally b. Bias (b) can be disabled by setting bias_init to None.

RMSProp Optimizer¶

The RMSprop optimizer is similar to the gradient descent algorithm with momentum. The RMSprop optimizer restricts the oscillations in the vertical direction. Therefore, we can increase our learning rate allowing our algorithm to take larger steps in the horizontal direction converging faster.

Graphs and Observations¶

  • We run update 5 episodes in each iteration. The plots are plotted against number of episodes vs rewards and number of episodes vs average value of states
  • The average reward plots stays at 0 initially and then after about 200 episodes we see change in reward achieved.
  • The average predicted Q increases quiet smoothly.

Comparison with the actual paper¶

  • As each epoch in the original experiment made more updates it's difficult to directly compare.
  • Each epoch in paper: 50000 updates. Our average epoch: 1200 steps
  • We observe no significant change in reward till: 1,200 epochs. (Due to lack of computation power it was difficult to perform more computation.)
  • The paper saw a general increasing trend in the state values which is observed in our case as well. (Updates are broken in batches.)
